The list of technologies includes:

*   **[Symmetric digital subscriber line](/Symmetric_digital_subscriber_line) (SDSL)**: An umbrella term for any xDSL where the bitrate is equal in both directions.
    *   **[ISDN digital subscriber line](/ISDN_digital_subscriber_line) (IDSL)**: An ISDN-based technology providing 144 kbit/s symmetric over one pair.
    *   **[High-bit-rate digital subscriber line](/High-bit-rate_digital_subscriber_line) (HDSL)**: ITU-T G.991.1, the first DSL to use a higher frequency spectrum than ISDN, offering 1,544 kbit/s and 2,048 kbit/s symmetric services.
    *   **[High-bit-rate digital subscriber line 2/4](/High-bit-rate_digital_subscriber_line_2) (HDSL2, HDSL4)**: An ANSI standard for 1,544 kbit/s symmetric over one pair (HDSL2) or two pairs (HDSL4).
    *   **[Symmetric digital subscriber line](/Symmetric_digital_subscriber_line) (SDSL)**: A specific proprietary technology, up to 1,544 kbit/s symmetric on one pair.
    *   **[Single-pair high-speed digital subscriber line](/Single-pair_high-speed_digital_subscriber_line) (G.SHDSL)**: ITU-T G.991.2, the standardized successor to HDSL and proprietary SDSL, supporting up to 5,696 kbit/s per pair, with up to four pairs.
*   **[Asymmetric digital subscriber line](/Asymmetric_digital_subscriber_line) (ADSL)**: An umbrella term for xDSL where the downstream bitrate is greater than the upstream.
    *   **[ANSI T1.413 Issue 2](/ANSI_T1.413_Issue_2)**: Up to 8 Mbit/s down and 1 Mbit/s up.
    *   **[G.dmt](/G.dmt)** (ITU-T G.992.1): Up to 10 Mbit/s down and 1 Mbit/s up.
    *   **[G.lite](/G.lite)** (ITU-T G.992.2): More resistant to noise and attenuation, up to 1,536 kbit/s down and 512 kbit/s up.
    *   **[Asymmetric digital subscriber line 2](/Asymmetric_digital_subscriber_line_2) (ADSL2)** (ITU-T G.992.3): Up to 12 Mbit/s down and 3.5 Mbit/s up.
    *   **[Asymmetric digital subscriber line 2 plus](/Asymmetric_digital_subscriber_line_2_plus) (ADSL2+)** (ITU-T G.992.5): Up to 24 Mbit/s down and 3.5 Mbit/s up.
*   **[Very-high-bit-rate digital subscriber line](/Very-high-bit-rate_digital_subscriber_line) (VDSL)** (ITU-T G.993.1): Up to 52 Mbit/s down and 16 Mbit/s up.
*   **[Very-high-bit-rate digital subscriber line 2](/Very-high-bit-rate_digital_subscriber_line_2) (VDSL2)** (ITU-T G.993.2): An improved VDSL, compatible with ADSL2+, with a combined upstream and downstream rate up to 200 Mbit/s. [25] The [G.vector](/G.vector) crosstalk cancelling feature (ITU-T G.993.5) can increase its range at a given bitrate, achieving 100 Mbit/s at up to 500 meters. [26]
*   **[G.fast](/G.fast)** (ITU-T G.9700 and G.9701): [27] Aims for approximately 1 Gbit/s aggregate speed at 100m. [28] Approved in December 2014, with deployments planned for 2016. [29] [30]
*   **XG-FAST**: An even more ambitious standard allowing for up to 10 Gbit/s on copper twisted pair, but only over laughably short distances of up to 30 meters. Real-world tests have shown 8 Gbit/s on 30-meter lines. [31] [32] [33]
*   **[Bonded DSL Rings](/Bonded_DSL_Rings) (DSL Rings)**: A shared ring topology at 400 Mbit/s.
*   **[Cable/DSL gateway](/Cable/DSL_gateway)**
*   **[Etherloop](/Etherloop)** Ethernet local loop
*   **High-speed voice and data link**
*   **[Rate-Adaptive Digital Subscriber Line](/Rate-Adaptive_Digital_Subscriber_Line) (RADSL)**: Designed to increase range and noise tolerance by sacrificing upstream speed.
*   **[Uni-DSL](/Uni-DSL) (Uni digital subscriber line or UDSL)**: A technology from Texas Instruments, backward compatible with all DMT standards.
*   **[Hybrid Access Networks](/Hybrid_Access_Networks)**: Combine an existing xDSL deployment with a wireless network like [LTE](/LTE_(telecommunication)) to increase bandwidth by balancing traffic over both networks. [34]

The severe line-length limitations impose a hard ceiling on data transmission rates. Technologies like [VDSL](/VDSL) provide very high speeds but only over very short ranges, making them suitable for delivering [triple play](/Triple_play_(telecommunications)) services in network architectures like [fiber to the curb](/Fiber_to_the_curb).

**Terabit DSL** is a theoretical proposal that suggests using the space between the dielectrics on copper twisted pair lines as waveguides for 300 GHz signals. This could offer speeds of up to 1 terabit per second at 100 meters, 100 gigabits per second at 300 meters, and 10 gigabits per second at 500 meters. [35] [36] The first experiments were conducted with parallel, untwisted copper lines inside a metal pipe to simulate the armoring in large [telephone cables](/Telephone_cable). [37] [38] Whether this ever escapes the lab is anyone's guess.

